Predicting NJ Transit Train Delays During the COVID-19 Pandemic

Jiaxuan Lyu, Jiamin Tan

2020/12/15

1. Introduction


The COVID-19 pandemic brought lots of changes in peoples daily lives. COVID-19 is caused by a new coronavirus (called SARS-CoV-2) and can generate symptoms such as fever, cough, trouble breathing and etc. (CDC, 2020). The World Health Organization suggests people to avoid COVID by wearing masks and keeping social distance (WHO, 2020). As the largest statewide public transit system in the US, New Jersey Transit is usually busy. When a major delay happened in February this year, severe crowding was observed in many of its stations. Under the pandemic, keeping a safe and healthy environment is always the first motive for public transportation services. In this project, we used a linear regression model to predict short-time delays of New Jersey Transit trains to help station staffs regulate passengers movements in stations to keep social distancing.

The New Jersey Transit data we used is provided by Pranav Badami and mzhang13 on Kaggle. From the dataset, we selected data from March, April and May 2020 as the pandemic started in the US. After performing exploratory data analysis, we feature engineered both spatial and temporal features to fit our model. Moreover, we added weather data as features because weather condition like gust and visibility can be related to whether a train will delay or not.

Our model is proved generalizable after running a k-fold cross validation - the model works well on predicting short-time delays (0~5 minutes) at all stations. Although it becomes less accurate when predicting longer-time delays, it does not affect the overall use case of our model. Under the pandemic, our model can provide accurate predictions of short-time delays requires station staffs to act earlier and give guidance for social distancing, in turn ensuring passengers safety at stations and on platforms.

We also make a video that demonstrates our models use case. The video could be viewed here.

# Quantile break functions
qBr <- function(df, variable, rnd) {
  if (missing(rnd)) {
    as.character(quantile(round(df[[variable]],0),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T))
  } else if (rnd == FALSE | rnd == F) {
    as.character(formatC(quantile(df[[variable]]), digits = 3),
                 c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T)
  }
}

q5 <- function(variable) {as.factor(ntile(variable, 5))}

2.2.1 Transit Data
transit2003 <- read.csv("C://MUSA508/Final Project/2020_03.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
transit2004 <- read.csv("C://MUSA508/Final Project/2020_04.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
transit2005 <- read.csv("C://MUSA508/Final Project/2020_05.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)

# get rid of NAs and focus on the Main/Bergen County Line
dat <- rbind(transit2003, transit2004, transit2005) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  filter(line == "Main Line" )

In this project, we used the New Jersey Transit data from Kaggle. We chose March, April and May data from year 2020, the time at the early phase of the COVID-19 pandemic.

Due to the interest of data size, we only pick the Main-Bergen County Line from all New Jersey Transit lines. The line is selected because it ran through counties with the most COVID-19 cases confirmed per one million people in New Jersey (Google News). Additionally, for later analysis, we used the lubricate package in R to extract month, day, hour, minute and 60-minute interval from the dataset.

Moreover, based on the extracted time, we created new features. We group the trains by periods of the day, such as morningRush, dayTime and eveningRush. Specifically, we defined 1-6 am transit as dawn, 7-9 am as morningRush, 11am-3pm as dayTime, and 4-8pm as eveningRush, and 9-12 pm as nightTime. In addition, we grouped the trains by day of week, classifying them as Sat/Sun, Mon/Fri and Others.

# interval 60
dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(scheduled_time = as_datetime(scheduled_time, tz = "America/New_York"),
         actual_time = as_datetime(actual_time, tz = "America/New_York")) %>%
  mutate(train_id = as.numeric(train_id), # conversion for specifying the direction
         direction = ifelse(train_id%%2 == 0, "toHoboken", "fromHoboken"), # specify the direction
         # floor hour and data using scheduled time
         interval60 = floor_date(ymd_hms(scheduled_time), unit = hours(x = 1)),
         # scheduled month, day, hour, minute
         month = month(interval60), 
         day = day(interval60),
         hour = hour(interval60),
         minute = minute(scheduled_time),
         # scheduled time in decimal format
         time = hour + minute/60,
         # period of the day
         potd = ifelse(hour > 0 & hour < 7, "dawn", 
                       ifelse(hour < 10, "morningRush", 
                              ifelse(hour < 16, "dayTime",
                                     ifelse(hour < 21, "eveningRush", "nightTime")))),
         # day of the week
         dotw = lubridate::wday(interval60, label = TRUE),
         # whether "Mon/Fri", "Sat/Sun", or "Other" days
         dotw2 = ifelse(dotw == "Fri" | dotw == "Mon", "Mon/Fri", ifelse(dotw == "Sun" | dotw == "Sat", "Sat/Sun", "Other")),
         # actual month, day, hour, minute
         act_month = month(actual_time),
         act_day = day(actual_time),
         act_hour = hour(actual_time),
         act_minute = minute(actual_time), 
         # actual time in decimal format
         act_time = act_hour + act_minute/60) 


# create a unique identifier for each row with concatenated date and train_id
dat$unique <- paste(dat$date, dat$train_id , sep = " ")

2.2.4 Weather Data

Due to spatial autocorrelation and data availability, we applied the weather data in New York City to all the stations on the line. The weather data in NYC are extractced by using riem package in R.

# get weather data
weatherNY <- riem_measures(station = "NYC", date_start = "2020-03-01", date_end = "2020-05-17") %>% 
  dplyr::select(valid, drct, sknt, p01i, vsby, gust)%>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
  mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = lubridate::wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(interval60) %>%
  summarize(Wind_Drect = max(drct),
            Precipitation = sum(p01i),
            Wind_Speed = max(sknt),
            Visibility = max(vsby),
            Gust = max(gust))

4. Feature Engineering


4.1 Delay for Previous station and Next Station at Previous Hour

#1.get the total delay of previous hour
# get the total delay of each "'from' 'to'" pair within the 1 hour period of its floor hour
sumDelayBtwStops <- dat %>% 
  group_by(from_id, to_id, direction, month, day, hour) %>% 
  summarise(delay1 = sum(delay_minutes)) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# create a new column for later use
sumDelayBtwStops$preDelay <- 0

# for each "'from' 'to'" pair in its own 1-hour period floor hour, 
# get the total delay of the previous 1-hour period
for (i in 1:(nrow(sumDelayBtwStops) - 1)){
  if(sumDelayBtwStops[i+1, 4] == sumDelayBtwStops[i, 4] & 
     sumDelayBtwStops[i+1, 5] == sumDelayBtwStops[i, 5] &
     sumDelayBtwStops[i+1, 6] == (sumDelayBtwStops[i, 6] + 1)){
    sumDelayBtwStops[i+1, 8] = sumDelayBtwStops[i, 7]
  }
}

# merge to get the total delay of the previous 1-hour period of each "'from' 'to'" pair
dat2 <- merge(dat, sumDelayBtwStops)
# assigning an ID to each row for reference use
dat$ID <- 1:nrow(dat)
# following 3 lines just to restore the merged data into the original order for later use
dat3 <- merge(dat, dat2)
dat4 <- dat3[order(dat3$ID),]
rownames(dat4) <- 1:nrow(dat4)


# mutating two columns of the total delay happened in the 1-hour floor hour in either
# previous "'from' 'to'" pairs or next "'from' 'to'" pairs
dat5 <- dat4 %>% 
  dplyr::select(train_id, month, day, preDelay) %>% 
  group_by(train_id, month, day) %>% 
  # shift the column down by 1 cell to get delay of the previous "'from' 'to'" delay
  mutate(preDelay = dplyr::lag(preDelay), 
         # shift the column up by 1 cell to get delay of the next "'from' 'to'" delay
         nextDelay = dplyr::lead(preDelay))


# merge the result to the original data
dat$preDelay <- dat5$preDelay
dat$nextDelay <- dat5$nextDelay

Other than the features that we made based on time, we aim to engineer a feature that demonstrates spatial influence and time influence. To illustrate, the transit line works as a network, and the delay minutes between stops are correlated. If we are at the second stop, the delays at the first stop (previous stop) and delay at the third stop (next stop) will influence the delay at current stop. Moreover, if there were severe delay at the previous hour, there might be delay at current.
Based on these considerations, we made two features. The first feature, preDelay is the summarized delay in previous one hour at previous station, and the second feature, nextDelay is the summarized delay in previous one hour at next station.

#predelay
ggplot(dat, aes(x=preDelay))+
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill="#66B2FF", color="#0066CC") +
  labs(x = "Previous Station Delay Minutes in Previous Hour",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Fig10. Histogram of previous station delay in Previous One Hour") +

We also made a feature that summarize cumulative delay minutes for one train in one day (cumulative delay). When the train is in service on the day we want to predict, we are not able to summarize cumulative delay on that day because the delay has not happen yet. Therefore, we will continue engineering this feature at the later part. Same to the nextDelay feature.
But in order to have a sense about how the feature looks like, we make Figure 14. Figure 14 shows there is a linear relationship between the cumulative delay feature and real-time delay minutes. We can see that they are positively related.

4.3 Cumulative Delay Over Space (5 stops away: Previous)

# cumulative delay 5 stops away on the day (previous 5 stops)
dat <- dat %>% 
  group_by(unique) %>% 
  mutate(cumulative_delay_5stopsAway = dplyr::lag(cumulative_delay, n = 5))

As mentioned at earlier part, we continue engineering our cumulative delay feature. Under the real world condition, we are not able to get cumulative delay for the train at current station, but we are able to obtain cumulative delay for the train at previous five stops away. We believe there will be enough time for the station staffs to prepare guidance plans if the train is currently five stops away.

4.4 Distance Between Two Stops and Speed

# get the time difference 
dat <- dat %>%
  group_by(unique) %>%
  # between the scheduled departure time
  mutate(timeDiff = time - lag(time, default = time[1]),
         # between the actual departure time
         act_timeDiff = act_time - lag(act_time, default = act_time[1]))
# deal with negative value caused by crossing midnight
dat$timeDiff[dat$timeDiff<0] <- dat$timeDiff[dat$timeDiff<0] + 24  
dat$act_timeDiff[dat$act_timeDiff<0] <- dat$act_timeDiff[dat$act_timeDiff<0] + 24 
# get unique "'from' 'to'" pairs
dat6 <- dat %>%
  group_by(from, to) %>%
  count() %>%
  dplyr::select(-n)

# get the from and to coordinates for the unique "'from' 'to'" pairs
colnames(stops) <- c("from", "from_lat", "from_lon")
dat6 <- merge(dat6, stops, by = "from", all.x = TRUE)
colnames(stops) <- c("to", "to_lat", "to_lon")
dat6 <- merge(dat6, stops, by = "to", all.x = TRUE)

dat6 <- dat6[ , c(2,1,3,4,5,6)]

# calculate the (great circle/Euclidean (since using coordinates in a small scale)) distance
# of each unique "'from' 'to'" pair
for (i in 1:nrow(dat6)){
  dat6$dist[i] <- distm(c(dat6[i, 4], dat6[i, 3]), c(dat6[i, 6], dat6[i, 5]), fun = distHaversine)
}

# merge the distance to the original data
dat <- merge(dat, dat6, by = c("from", "to"))

# get the scheduled and actual speed between each "'from' 'to'" pair
dat$avgSpeed <- dat$dist/(dat$timeDiff + 0.00001) # cannot divided by 0
dat$act_avgSpeed <- dat$dist/(dat$act_timeDiff + 0.00001)

Furthermore, we calculated the distance between two stops and the time differences for the train to pass to stops. Then we use the distances and time differences to calculate the scheduled speed and actual speed between each two-stop sequence.

ggplot(data=dat, aes(x=delay_minutes, y=avgSpeed))+
  geom_point(color="#003366", alpha=0.5) +
  labs(x = "Delay Minutes",
       y = "Average Speed of each trip",
       title = "Fig16. Average Speed of each trip vs. Delay Minutes")+
  plotTheme+
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12),
        plot.title =  element_text(size = 14))

Finally, we made a 7-day time lag for previous features. There are two reasons for doing this. First, based on Figure 3, there are cyclical variations among delay minutes, and trains will most likely to repeat their traveling behavior in a weekly basis. Second, as mentioned when calculating the cumulative delay minutes, there is no way to know the cumulative delay of the entire trip on the day that we are predicting. Therefore we decide to make a 7-day lag for delay minutes, time difference, summarized previous 1-hour delay at previous station, summarized previous 1-hour delay at next station, cumulative delay and actual average speed.
From Figure 17, we could see that these two features are positively correlated, and r is 0.68.

5. Model


5.1 Split Test/Train Dataset

train.set <- dat_new %>% 
  filter(month == 3 | month == 4)

test.set <- dat_new %>% 
  filter(month == 5)

We will use data from March 8 to April 30 to train our model and use data from May 1 to May 16 to validate the model.


5.2 Regression

reg <- lm(cd_delay_minutes ~ train_id + from + to  + 
            cd_dotw2 + cd_potd + cd_avgSpeed + cd_cumulative_delay_5stopsAway +
            + cd_Wind_Drect +cd_Wind_Speed + cd_Gust + cd_Precipitation +
            cd_Visibility+ sd_delay_minutes + sd_cumulative_delay + sd_preDelay + sd_nextDelay,
          data = train.set)

Here are all the independent variables we used:

  • Under current date

    • train id

    • departure station

    • arrival station

    • day of the week

    • period of the day

    • scheduled speed between the departure and arrival station

    • cumulative delay minutes from 5 stops away

    • wind direction

    • wind speed

    • gust

    • precipitation

    • visibility

  • From 7 days ago

    • delay minutes of the same train at the same station

    • cumulative delay of the same train up to the station of prediction

    • total delay minutes at the previous station in the previous floor hour period

    • total delay minutes at the next station in the previous floor hour period

4.4 Mean Absolute Error

In order to evaluate the model, we calculate the mean absolute error (MAE).

#Mean Absolute Error

test.set %>%
  mutate(delay = case_when(cd_delay_minutes <= 2 ~ "0-2 min",
                           cd_delay_minutes > 2 & cd_delay_minutes <=5 ~ "2-5 min",
                           cd_delay_minutes > 5 & cd_delay_minutes <= 10 ~ "5-10 min",
                           cd_delay_minutes > 10 & cd_delay_minutes <= 15 ~ "10-15 min",
                           cd_delay_minutes > 15 & cd_delay_minutes <= 20 ~ "15-20 min",

                           cd_delay_minutes > 25 & cd_delay_minutes <= 30 ~ "25-30 min",
                           cd_delay_minutes > 30 ~ "over 30 min")) %>%

We classify the delay minutes as eight groups and show the MAE for each group. From Table 1, we could see that our model works best on predicting 2-5 minutes delays. The MAE is less than 1, which is less than 1 minutes, which is very useful to help workers regulate passengers to keep social distancing. However, our model does not do well on predicting long-time delays, especially for delays which are longer than 20 minutes. We will further discuss this issue in the discussion section.

Figure 22 shows the relationship between observed delay minutes and the predicted delay minutes. Specifically, we over predicted the delays between 0 to 2 minutes, and under predicted the delays between 2 to 10 minutes. This is good for our use case, because by slightly counting more delays as around 2-5 minutes, station staffs will not miss potential crowding took place in the station.
One reason for the higher accuracy for the 0-2 and 2-5 minutes groups is because we have much more training data from those two time groups. For time groups, especially 15-20 minutes, 20-25 minutes, 25-30 minutes and over 20 minutes, they have much fewer data. The lack of data might cause lower accuracy for those groups.

We also performed a 100-fold cross validation using the training data of March and April in 2020. Table 6 shows the overall MAE of the cross validation result. 6. Discussion


Under normal circumstances, it is not meaningful to predict a 3-minute delay of a train. Even if an accurate model can tell the passengers to expect a 3-minutes delay, one can imagine the passengers attitude will be like So what? Under the pandemic, ironically, predicting a 3-mintute train delay matters because most people think such delay does not matter. Passengers will not show up late on a platform or at a station because of a 3-minute delay, so the crowds waiting for the delayed trains can discourage social distancing from happening. Such behavior can be extremely dangerous for spreading the virus among passengers. We believe train service providers, such as New Jersey Transit, should be responsible for keeping their passengers safer as they can provide guidance for social distancing and regulate the passenger circulation in stations. Our model is built for them to prepare ahead of time.

The latest input data for our predictive model is the cumulative delay of the target train from 5 stops away on the day of prediction. We believe such design saves enough time for station staff to prepare their plans. Other input data can also be easily obtained from data generated seven days ago or from the local weather forecast services. We only used NYC weather data at present due to free data sources availability online, but we believe NJ Transit should have the resources to get more local weather data and improve the model.

In terms of the accuracy of our model, only calculating the overall MAE could be meaningless for our use case. Therefore, by looking at the MAE categorized by the tests true delay time, we found the MAE for predicting the 2 to 5 minutes delay is less than 1 minute. This means our model should be accurate enough to tell the staffs whether they need to prepare for the congestion of crowds. As we found in Figure 22, we overly estimated the delays between 0 and 2 minutes, while under estimated the delays between 5 and 10 minutes. That means our prediction categorized more circumstances into the 2 to 5 minutes scenario in which guidance should be prepared. In that way, we can be more confident not to miss any potential crowding happened due to short time delays.

Although our model showed drawbacks when predicting for longer delays, we do not think those will affect the general use case of this model. In fact, longer delays are not usually caused by time-space factors we examined in this project. According to the publicized official reasons of delays on Twitter (@ NJTRANSIT_MBPJ), long time delays are usually caused by things like mechanical problem, maintenance, or even police activities. Therefore, to get more accurate prediction for longer delays, NJ Transit should add those factors into consideration, if they decide to adopt our model.

Lastly, the data we used from Kaggle was neither official, nor completed. If NJ Transit is interest in using our model, they should use their official data collected from the train operations. We also believe that if they can expand the model to fit the entire system, the model should be even more accurate. This is because for the network delays engineered in our dataset, we could only get data on the Main-Bergen County Line that we focused on. However, for large stations, several lines will share the tracks and platforms, the network delays will be more accurate when all the lines are taken into account. In this way, the delays of train in and out larger transferring stations can explain more about the delay behavior happening in the system. Thus, if NJ Transit use this model in the future, they can provide more comprehensive data so that model will become usable.

7. Conclusion


In conclusion, the OLS model we developed for predicting short time train delays will be useful for helping station staffs prepare guidance for crowd congestions. It predicts well on short-time delays, in turn reach our goal to help transit workers organize customers to keep social distance. We will also encourage NJ Transit to add more data and variables of their train and track condition which are highly relevant to train delays. With the motivation to keep passenger safe and healthy, we recommend the New Jersey Transit to use our model as the second wave of COVID-19 pandemic hitting the US.
